Definition: Defines the %  response for the front brakes of the vehicle. 50% indicates the brake torque is equal to the rear brakes, <50% indicates there is a larger torque applied at the rear
Maximum braking torque which can be applied through the brakes system
The lock percentage of the differential when coasting (no load applied)
The lock percentage of the differential under power. This determines the torque split between the left and right wheels
Units: % (100% is fully locked, 0% is fully unlocked)

Definition: The preload applied to the differential. A torque difference of X is required to unlock differential
The effective wheel rate of the front anti roll bar
The effective wheel rate of the rear anti roll bar
The position of the center of mass along the vehicles length
Units: % of wheelbase (50% indicates equally distribution, <50% indicates rear bias)

Definition: The distance from the centre-point of the rear wheels to the centre-point of the front wheels
The spring rate of the front shocks “bump stops”
The damping contribution of the front dampers where it is “compressing” due to a slow impact.
The damping contribution of the front dampers where it is “compressing” due to a fast impact.
The damping contribution of the front dampers where it is “rebounding” from a slow impact.
Total length of suspension trave for the front shocks
Adjusts the ride height of the vehicle. Similar to coil-over adjustment of a vehicle
The effective spring rate of the suspension corner from the wheel contact
The angles of the front wheels looking from a front-view. Negative camber is where the bottom-most section of the tyre is further outboard then the top-most
The angle of the front wheels from a top-view perspective. Negative values represent the front wheels “toeing inwards” from neutral.
The effective distance from the contact points of the front left to the front right wheel
Adjusts the ride height of the vehicle. Similar to coil-over adjustment of a vehicle
The effective spring rate of the suspension corner from the wheel contact
The angles of the rear wheels looking from a front-view. Negative camber is where the bottom-most section of the tyre is further outboard then the top-most
The angle of the rear wheels from a top-view perspective. Negative values represent the rear wheels “toeing inwards” from neutral.
The effective distance from the contact points of the rear left to the rear right wheel
The damping contribution of the front dampers where it is “rebounding” from a fast impact.
The spring rate of the rear shocks “bump stops”
The damping contribution of the rear dampers where it is “compressing” due to a slow impact.
The damping contribution of the rear dampers where it is “compressing” due to a fast impact.
The damping contribution of the rear dampers where it is “rebounding” from a fast impact.
The damping contribution of the rear dampers where it is “rebounding” from a slow impact.
Total length of suspension trave for the rear shocks
The effective static pressure of the front tyre
The effective static pressure of the rear tyre
